Build a Model

https://www.tidymodels.org/start/models/

Load and plot data

library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
library(broom.mixed)
library(dotwhisker)
library(rstanarm)

urchins <-
  read_csv("https://tidymodels.org/start/models/urchins.csv") %>%
  setNames(c("food_regime", "initial_volume", "width")) %>%
  mutate(food_regime = factor(food_regime, levels = c("Initial", "Low", "High")))
summary(urchins)

              Mean   :20.88   Mean   :0.07237  
              3rd Qu.:26.00   3rd Qu.:0.08450  
              Max.   :47.50   Max.   :0.16300

Note: notice the grouped plotting of the data with group and col arguments of aes()

ggplot(urchins,
       aes(x = initial_volume,
           y = width,
           group = food_regime,
           col = food_regime)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = .7)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Steps of building a Model

  • Define Model as a Formula, e.g.Â y ~ x1 + x2

  • Specify the âfunctional formâ of a model and declare it with the respective function, e.g.Â âlinear regressionâ with linear_reg()

  • Choose a computational engine for actually fitting or training a model with set_engine()

  • Estimate or train the model using fit()

lm_fit <- linear_reg() |> 
  set_engine("lm") |> 
  fit(width ~ initial_volume * food_regime, data = urchins) 

tidy(lm_fit, conf.int = TRUE)

Make Predictions

Generate new data for a simulation (three times to see if bayesian will have differneces):

new_points <- expand.grid(initial_volume = 20, 
                          food_regime = c("Initial", "Low", "High")) |> arrange(food_regime)
new_points
  initial_volume food_regime
1             20     Initial
2             20         Low
3             20        High

Use predict() to generate predictions in a standardized way

mean_pred <- predict(lm_fit, new_data = new_points)
conf_int_pred <- predict(lm_fit, 
                         new_data = new_points, 
                         type = "conf_int")
plot_data <- 
  new_points %>% 
  bind_cols(mean_pred) %>% 
  bind_cols(conf_int_pred)

plot_data
  initial_volume food_regime      .pred .pred_lower .pred_upper
1             20     Initial 0.06421443  0.05549934  0.07292952
2             20         Low 0.05880940  0.04986251  0.06775629
3             20        High 0.09613343  0.08696233  0.10530453
# and plot:
ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = food_regime, col = food_regime)) + 
  geom_point(aes(y = .pred)) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = .pred_lower, 
                    ymax = .pred_upper),
                width = .2) + 
  labs(y = "urchin size")

Model with different Engine

To use a different modeling engine (e.g.Â Stan) simply replace the set_engine() part and define any needed additional arguments (e.g.Â prior distributions).

Example for the same analysis using a Bayesian approach with Stan:

set.seed(123)
# set the prior distribution
prior_dist <- rstanarm::student_t(df = 1)

bayes_mod <-   
  linear_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("stan", 
             prior_intercept = prior_dist, 
             prior = prior_dist) 

bayes_fit <- 
  bayes_mod %>% 
  fit(width ~ initial_volume * food_regime, data = urchins)

tidy(bayes_fit, conf.int = TRUE)
# A tibble: 6 Ã 5
  term                            estimate std.error  conf.low conf.high
  <chr>                              <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
1 (Intercept)                     0.0334    0.00947   0.0171    0.0493  
2 initial_volume                  0.00155   0.000392  0.000885  0.00222 
3 food_regimeLow                  0.0194    0.0135   -0.00178   0.0417  
4 food_regimeHigh                 0.0207    0.0140   -0.00287   0.0457  
5 initial_volume:food_regimeLow  -0.00125   0.000520 -0.00211  -0.000389
6 initial_volume:food_regimeHigh  0.000551  0.000688 -0.000651  0.00168 
bayes_plot_data <- 
  new_points %>% 
  bind_cols(predict(bayes_fit, new_data = new_points)) %>% 
  bind_cols(predict(bayes_fit, new_data = new_points, type = "conf_int"))

ggplot(bayes_plot_data, aes(x = food_regime, col = food_regime)) + 
  geom_point(aes(y = .pred)) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = .pred_lower, ymax = .pred_upper), width = .2) + 
  labs(y = "urchin size") + 
  ggtitle("Bayesian model with t(1) prior distribution")
